05439nam a22007215i 9781501740176DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019026366  a97815017401767 a10.1515/97815017401762doi  a(DE-B1597)533948  a(OCoLC)1110124373  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHQ1073.5.T5 4aHQ1073.5.T5 7aPOL0540002bisacsh04a306.095932231 aPearson, Trais, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSovereign Necropolis :bThe Politics of Death in Semi-Colonial Siam /cTrais Pearson. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (252 p.) :b8 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tNote on Naming Conventions, Sources, Transcription, and Translation -- tIntroduction -- t1. Bad Death -- t2. Indemnity and Identity -- t3. Treaty Port Tort -- t4. Accidental Metaphysics -- t5. Morbid Subjects -- t6. Incisions and Inscriptions -- tConclusion -- tEpilogue: Spirits in a Material World -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy the 1890s, Siam (Thailand) was the last holdout against European imperialism in Southeast Asia. But the kingdom's exceptional status came with a substantial caveat: Bangkok, its bustling capital, was a port city that was subject to many of the same legal and fiscal constraints as other colonial treaty ports. Sovereign Necropolis offers new insight into turn-of-the-century Thai history by disinterring the forgotten stories of those who died "unnatural deaths" during this period and the work of the Siamese state to assert their rights in a pluralistic legal arena.Based on a neglected cache of inquest files compiled by the Siamese Ministry of the Capital, official correspondence, and newspaper accounts, Trais Pearson documents the piecemeal introduction of new forms of legal and medical concern for the dead. He reveals that the investigation of unnatural death demanded testimony from diverse strata of society: from the unlettered masses to the king himself. These cases raised questions about how to handle the dead-were they spirits to be placated, or legal subjects whose deaths demanded compensation?-as well as questions about jurisdiction, rights, and liability. Exhuming the history of imperial politics, transnational commerce, technology, and expertise, Sovereign Necropolis demonstrates how the state's response to global flows transformed the nature of legal subjectivity and politics in lasting ways. Sovereign Necropolis is a compelling exploration of the troubling lives of the dead in a cosmopolitan treaty port, and a notable contribution to the growing corpus of studies in science, law, and society in the non-Western world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aDeathxPolitical aspectszThailandxHistory. 0aDeathxProof and certificationzThailandxHistory. 0aPolitical culturezThailandxHistory. 0aThanatologyzThailandxHistory. 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory Of Medicine. 4aLegal History & Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Asian.2bisacsh  aImperialism, Thiland, legal history, medical history, Sovereignty.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gru